<self-adv>
You can try zoggy, a lablgtk interface builder, too :
http://www.maxence-g.net/Tools/zoggy/zoggy.html
</self-adv>
 
> What is essential for ocaml/gtk users (in my opinion) is a small
> description/example of ALL the available widgets, and it's basic
> methods.

You can check the Lablgtk hump for applications using LablGtk.
They are cllassified by the widget they use, so you should quickly find
examples for the widget you cant to use. Also, the lablgtk library
comes with a lot of useful examples.

http://caml.inria.fr/humps/lablgtk.html

Good luck,

